The PL spectra of GQDs are shown in Fig. 2(a), with the excitation wavelength dependence of the position of the PL peaks in the excitation wavelength range of 310 nm-360 nm. The PL emission peak position can be observed at 409 nm, where the most vigorous PL emission can be realized at the excitation wavelength of 330 nm. Furthermore, it can be seen that the GQDs have bright blue fluorescence in ethanol solution under UV lamp irradiation. Fig. 2(b) shows the PL spectra of GQDs in different concentrations of Cu2+ ion solutions, from which, under the same measurement environment and the same excitation wavelength (340 nm), the PL emission intensities of the GQDs gradually decreased with the increase of Cu2+ concentration (0–100 μm). In Fig. 2(c), the PL intensity (quenching effect) decreases almost linearly with increasing Cu2+ concentration. Its correlation coefficient R 2 is 0.9529, indicating that GQDs can be used for rapid and selective detection of Cu2+ ions in aqueous solution. Fig. 2(d) shows the UV–Vis absorption spectra of GQDs solution and GQDs + Cu2+ solution, from which it can be seen that GQDs had a clear optical characteristic absorption peak at 270 nm. The absorption peak of GQDs + Cu2+ at 270 nm disappeared after the addition of Cu2+ ions, indicating that Cu2+ ions altered the electronic properties of the surface/edge of the GQDs, thus suppressing the fluorescence emission of GQDs + Cu2+. Fig. 2(e) shows the image fitted by the Tauc plot method. The fitting calculation yields that C-C/C = C in the sp 2 carbon region induces an effective electron transition (
π → π ∗
) for GQDs, and the intrinsic energy gap of GQDs is 5.21 eV. Due to the presence of the characteristic functional groups (e.g., C-O, C = O, and C-NH2) at the surfaces/edge of the GQDs introduces the surface states in the GQDs system, and the indirect transitions of the surface states lead to GQDs with frequent fluorescence emission. The energy difference is 3.86 eV. The same fitting calculation method gives that the energy gap of GQDs + Cu2+ is 5.33 eV. The schematic diagrams of the ideal electronic energy levels and electron-leap channels of GQDs and GQDs + Cu2+ can be constructed as shown in Fig. 2(f) and (g). It can be noticed that the core electronic energy level structures of GQDs and GQDs + Cu2+ are the same. In the GQDs + Cu2+ luminescence system of Fig. 2(f), after the addition of GQDs to the Cu2+ ions, the electrons in the ground state are pumped by the light to jump to the empty electron state, and the electrons are relaxed through the non-radiative electron-jumping channels to the unfilled d orbitals of the Cu2+ ions, which cannot go back to the ground state, and the PL emission of the GQDs will not be realized. As a result, the PL emission of GQDs + Cu2+ was suppressed, producing a fluorescence quenching phenomenon.
